    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, so my tomato plants are looking kind of weird. The leaves on the bottom of the plants are turning all yellow, but the new growth at the top looks fine. Do you know what might be going on with them? I'm worried I'm doing something wrong with the soil.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It sounds like your tomato plants might be experiencing a common issue known as \"lower leaf scorch.\" This can be caused by a variety of factors, including too much direct sunlight, underwatering, or poor soil drainage. It's possible that the roots are not receiving enough moisture, causing the lower leaves to turn yellow and drop off. You can try increasing the frequency of watering, but make sure not to overwater, as this can also cause problems. \n\nIt's also worth checking the pH level of your soil, as tomatoes prefer a slightly acidic to neutral pH range. If your soil is too alkaline, it can cause nutrient deficiencies and scorching of the lower leaves. \n\nHowever, I must say that I'm a bit curious - you're not telling me that your soil is as dry as a desert, are you? I mean, I've heard of some gardeners who have to water their plants by the bucketload, but I'm not sure that's the case here.",
