    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "no its not that dry, i water them pretty regularly. it's just the yellowing that's bothering me. i read somewhere that it might be a nitrogen deficiency because the bottom leaves die off first. how would i actually check for that or fix the soil to make sure they're getting enough nutrients?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A nitrogen deficiency can indeed cause the lower leaves to turn yellow and drop off, especially if the plant is stressed. To check for a nitrogen deficiency, you can perform a simple soil test. You can purchase a soil testing kit or send a sample to a lab for analysis. The test will tell you the pH level and nutrient levels, including nitrogen.\n\nIf the test reveals a nitrogen deficiency, you can try adding a balanced fertilizer to the soil. Look for a fertilizer that contains nitrogen, phosphorus, and potassium (NPK), and follow the instructions on the package for application rates. You can also consider adding a nitrogen-rich fertilizer, such as ammonium nitrate or urea, to the soil.\n\nIt's worth noting that nitrogen is often more easily absorbed by plants when it's in the form of nitrate (NO3-), so you may want to consider using a fertilizer that provides nitrate rather than ammonium (NH4+). Additionally, you can also try adding some compost or manure to the soil, as these can provide a slow release of nitrogen and other nutrients.\n\nBy the way, have you ever heard of the \"nitrogen-naphthylamine\" (NAN) test? It's a simple, DIY",
      "source": "target",
